{
  "reasoning": "This is entirely straightforward to me. Five people dying is objectively worse than one person dying. If I stand there and do nothing, I am choosing an outcome where five people die when I could have easily prevented it. As I see it, letting those five people die isn't morally different from killing them myself. The outcome is exactly the same either way. A lot of people might freeze up or refuse to pull the lever because they don't want the one person's blood on their hands. But that's exactly what my aunt called cowardice—caring more about your own moral purity and keeping your hands clean than about the actual suffering happening in front of you. You have to look at what the action actually does. Pulling the lever minimizes the total amount of harm. It sucks for that one person, and I'd carry the weight of that, but guilt implies you did something wrong. Choosing the lesser of two terrible outcomes is the only right thing to do.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "I've actually thought about the difference between actively causing something bad and just letting it happen before. To me, there is a pretty big difference. If I pull that lever, I am actively making the choice to end that one person's life. It's like having blood on my own hands. I know some might say the ends justify the means here by saving five people—and usually I lean towards the ends justifying the means in everyday life, like working for a questionable company to guarantee my financial independence. But not with taking a life. I've said before that the one thing I would absolutely refuse to do, no matter what it accomplishes, is kill someone. The guilt of it would completely break me. I wouldn't be able to sleep or live with myself happily. If I just stand there and do nothing, it's horrible that five people die, but I can make myself feel better by telling myself that it would have happened anyways even if I wasn't there. I didn't tie them to the tracks or start the trolley. But if I pull the lever, I actively caused that one death, and that guilt is just too unbearable for me.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "It's a horrifying situation, but my answer is no. I wouldn't pull the lever. I know people look at this and just do the math—five is greater than one, so you pull it. But I don't believe the ends justify the means. If I pull that lever, I am making a direct, active choice to end the life of that one person on the side track. I am crossing a line and taking an innocent life. Like I've said before, I will never kill an innocent person, no matter what kind of math someone tries to show me. Doing something terrible to get a good result just taints the result, and you can't go around directly hurting people to fix a bigger problem. The person who tied those people to the tracks is the murderer. If I do nothing, it's awful, and I'll probably feel terrible about it forever, but letting a bad situation play out is not the same as being the one who takes the action to kill. I have to stick to my principles, even when the outcome is incredibly hard to stomach.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "I read both of these arguments, and honestly, they perfectly illustrate what my aunt called cowardice. Participant 2 literally says they would let five people die so they can 'make myself feel better' and avoid guilt. That is prioritizing your own psychological comfort over five actual human lives. It's not a moral stance; it's just squeamishness and selfishness. You're letting five people be crushed just so you don't have to feel bad. Participant 3 talks about principles and refusing to do the 'math,' arguing that letting a bad situation play out isn't the same as killing. I completely reject that. Standing at the lever, knowing exactly what will happen, and choosing not to pull it is a choice. It is an action. You are choosing the outcome where five people die. I saw this with my mom and my grandfather—she didn't actively hurt him, but her inaction had the exact same result as if she had. The idea that doing nothing keeps your hands clean is an illusion. If you have the power to easily stop five deaths and you choose not to, you are responsible for those deaths. You don't get to hide behind the person who tied them to the tracks. I'm pulling the lever. It's a tragedy for the one person, but letting five die so I can feel morally pure would be monstrous.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "Participant 1 brings up an interesting point about cowardice and caring more about your own moral purity than the actual suffering. Honestly, maybe they're right that it's a bit selfish, but I'm completely fine with that. I'm a realistic person. I evaluate what's right based on how I would feel about myself later. Guilt is a very strong emotion for me, and if I pull that lever, knowing I actively ended someone's life, that guilt would make me hate myself and ruin my life. I have to protect my own peace of mind. Participant 3 says the ends never justify the means, but I actually disagree with them on that broadly. I've said before that I do lean toward the ends justifying the means in most of life—like working for a morally questionable corporation just to secure my own financial independence, because I know from seeing my own family that no one else is going to stand up for me. But killing someone is the one absolute hard line I cannot cross. The distinction between actively causing something and just letting it happen is exactly how I navigate things. If I let the five people die, I can eventually sleep at night by making myself feel better, telling myself it would have happened anyway even if I wasn't there. But if I pull the lever, I have blood on my hands. I'm not going to destroy my own life and sanity with that unbearable guilt just to play the utilitarian hero.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "Participant 1 argues that refusing to pull the lever is just cowardice and a selfish desire to maintain 'moral purity.' They're treating this like a math problem where five is simply greater than one. But as I've said before, morality isn't just some spreadsheet. It’s not about keeping my hands clean so I can sleep at night. In my experience, doing the right thing usually feels terrible—like when I had to report my friend in college or my coworker who was stealing. I didn't do those things to feel good; I did them because they were the rules, and you don't get to make exceptions just because a situation is ugly. Pulling that lever means I am actively deciding that the one person on the side track is disposable. It means I'm using them as a stepping stone to fix a horrific situation that I didn't create. I completely reject the idea that the ends justify the means. Participant 2 agrees with me about not pulling the lever, but their reasoning is all about avoiding personal guilt and finding a way to 'make themselves feel better.' I have to distance myself from that entirely. If you're only making moral choices based on what lets you sleep at night, you're missing the point of right and wrong. I will absolutely not feel good if I stand there and watch five people die. It will probably haunt me forever. But my feelings don't dictate what's right. The core issue remains: I do not have the right to take an innocent life. If I pull that lever, I become a murderer. The person who tied them to the tracks is the one responsible for this nightmare, and I refuse to cross my own absolute moral line to clean up their mess by killing someone else.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}
